tlassian Confluence MCP Server"><p>Recently, I needed to import issues from Atlassian Jira into Claude Code.</p><p>It&apos;s so simple:</p><pre><code class="language-`">claude mcp add atlassian --transport sse &quot;https://mcp.atlassian.com/v1/sse&quot; --scope user</code></pre><p>After that, the Atlassian MCP Server is registered.</p><p>Check if the MCP server is added afterward:</p><pre><code>claude mcp list</code></pre><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image-2.png" class="kg-image" alt="Connect Claude Code with Atlassian Jira and Atlassian Confluence MCP Server" loading="lazy" width="776" height="89" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/image-2.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image-2.png 776w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"></figure><p>You may need to restart the French guy (Claude Code). </p><p>Type /mcp and select the Atlassian MCP server to authenticate. You will then be forwarded to this screen.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image-3.png" class="kg-image" alt="Connect Claude Code with Atlassian Jira and Atlassian Confluence MCP Server" loading="lazy" width="591" height="248"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Authenticate via /mcp</span></figcaption></figure><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/atlassian-mcp.png" class="kg-image" alt="Connect Claude Code with Atlassian Jira and Atlassian Confluence MCP Server" loading="lazy" width="882" height="1108" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/atlassian-mcp.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/atlassian-mcp.png 882w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Redirect to Atlassian while Authenticating the MCP Server</span></figcaption></figure><p>After that, you can query Jira and Confluence using Claude Code.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image-4.png" class="kg-image" alt="Connect Claude Code with Atlassian Jira and Atlassian Confluence MCP Server" loading="lazy" width="1004" height="614" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/image-4.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/image-4.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image-4.png 1004w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Calling the Atlassian MCP Server</span></figcaption></figure><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image-7.png" class="kg-image" alt="Connect Claude Code with Atlassian Jira and Atlassian Confluence MCP Server" loading="lazy" width="1404" height="229" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/image-7.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/image-7.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image-7.png 1404w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The example issues in the Sprint Backlog in Atlassian Jira.</span></figcaption></figure><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image-6.png" class="kg-image" alt="Connect Claude Code with Atlassian Jira and Atlassian Confluence MCP Server" loading="lazy" width="920" height="181" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/image-6.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image-6.png 920w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The results of querying the Jira Project issues</span></figcaption></figure><p>Happy task creation for Claude ;-)</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code]]></title><description><![CDATA[AI-powered C4 model and views: Analyze any codebase with Claude Code, generate a Structurizr-DSL based architecture model, and create architecture diagrams in minutes instead of hours.]]></description><link>https://www.workingsoftware.dev/ai-assisted-software-architecture-generating-the-c4-model-and-views-directly-from-code/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">698720518aaa4d000151d4f1</guid><category><![CDATA[Software Architecture]]></category><category><![CDATA[Software Architect]]></category><category><![CDATA[C4 Model]]></category><category><![CDATA[Claude Code]]></category><category><![CDATA[AI]]></category><category><![CDATA[Structurizr]]></category><category><![CDATA[Structurizr DSL]]></category><dc:creator><![CDATA[Patrick Roos]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 11 Feb 2026 21:21:32 GMT</pubDate><media:content url="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-White-Simple-Business-Blog-Banner.png" medium="image"/><content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-White-Simple-Business-Blog-Banner.png" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code"><p>Let me start with a short story.</p><p>Yesterday, a colleague showed me an app he had mostly <em>vibe-coded</em>. The product itself was interesting, but after the demo he said something that caught my attention:</p><blockquote>&#x201C;Let me show you the architecture.&#x201D;</blockquote><p>His instinct was to jump straight into the codebase and start navigating files and folders. Instead, I suggested a different approach.</p><p>Instead of browsing code, why don&#x2019;t we <strong>model the architecture first</strong>?</p><h2 id="skipping-code-browsing-starting-with-architecture">Skipping Code Browsing, Starting with Architecture</h2><p>The idea was simple: instead of mentally reverse-engineering the architecture from code, we create a <a href="https://c4model.com/?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">C4-based architecture model</a> using the <a href="https://docs.structurizr.com/dsl?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">Structurizr DSL</a> that provides all the relevant views at once.</p><p>With the help of <a href="https://claude.com/product/claude-code?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer"><strong>Claude Code</strong></a>, we were able to:</p><ul><li>analyze the codebase quickly,</li><li>generate a <a href="https://docs.structurizr.com/dsl?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">Structurizr DSL</a> model,</li><li>and refine it iteratively.</li></ul><p>Once the DSL was ready, we copied it into <a href="https://playground.structurizr.com/?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">playground.structurizr.com</a> and generated the defined diagrams.</p><p>Within minutes, we could <strong>navigate through the different C4 views</strong>:</p><ul><li><a href="https://c4model.com/diagrams/system-context?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">System Context Diagram</a></li><li><a href="https://c4model.com/diagrams/container?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">Container Diagram of the Software System</a></li><li><a href="https://c4model.com/diagrams/component?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">Component Diagram of the interesting Containers</a></li></ul><p>No guesswork. No scrolling through files. Just a hierarchical overview of the software architecture.</p><h2 id="the-%E2%80%9Cwait-a-second%E2%80%A6%E2%80%9D-moment">The &#x201C;Wait a Second&#x2026;&#x201D; Moment</h2><p>That experience sparked an idea.</p><p>What if this wasn&#x2019;t just a one-time experiment?</p><p>What if there is a <a href="https://code.claude.com/docs/en/skills?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer"><strong>Claude Code skill</strong></a> that does exactly this:</p><ul><li>Analyze an entire codebase</li><li>Derive an architecture model automatically</li><li>Generate a Structurizr DSL</li><li>Produce ready-to-use C4 diagrams</li></ul><p>In other words:<em> Architecture documentation as an AI-assisted, repeatable process.</em></p><h2 id="why-this-matters">Why This Matters</h2><p>Modern codebases evolve quickly, but architecture diagrams usually do not. If we can:</p><ul><li>generate architecture models quickly</li><li>keep them close to the code</li><li>and make them easy to browse and discuss</li></ul><p>then architecture becomes a <em>living artifact</em>, not a forgotten document.</p><h2 id="the-repository">The Repository</h2><p>I turned this idea into a first experiment, which you can find here &#x1F447;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"><a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://github.com/bitsmuggler/c4-skill?ref=workingsoftware.dev"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">GitHub - bitsmuggler/c4-skill: Claude Code skill to create a C4 model based on an existing code base</div><div class="kg-bookmark-description">Claude Code skill to create a C4 model based on an existing code base - bitsmuggler/c4-skill</div><div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/icon/pinned-octocat-093da3e6fa40-12.svg" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code"><span class="kg-bookmark-author">GitHub</span><span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">bitsmuggler</span></div></div><div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/thumbnail/c4-skill" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" onerror="this.style.display = &apos;none&apos;"></div></a></figure><h2 id="the-demo">The Demo</h2><p>About three years ago, I wrote an article about the <a href="https://supabase.com/?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">Supabase</a> architecture, where <a href="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/tech-stack-and-architecture-of-supabase/" rel="noreferrer">I analyzed the architecture</a> in a few hours. See the full blog post here &#x1F447;</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"><a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/tech-stack-and-architecture-of-supabase/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">Architecture and Technology Stack of Supabase &#x26A1;</div><div class="kg-bookmark-description">Supabase under the hood. This post shows you the high-level architecture and the technology stack of Supabase.</div><div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/icon/logo_small_icon_only-1-14.png" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code"><span class="kg-bookmark-author">workingsoftware.dev</span><span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Patrick Roos</span></div></div><div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/thumbnail/structurizr-75038-Supabase--7-.png" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" onerror="this.style.display = &apos;none&apos;"></div></a></figure><p>With this first draft of the C4-Architecture Claude Code skill, the process takes just minutes.</p><p>In the following screenshots, you&apos;ll see how Claude Code works with this new C4 model architecture skill.</p><h3 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h3><p>To use this additional C4 Claude Code architecture skill, you must clone the repository:</p><ul><li>Clone the repository into your Claude config directory</li><li>Symlink the command</li><li>Optional: Pull the required Docker images (for better initial performance)</li><li>Restart Claude Code</li></ul><h3 id="starting-the-analysis">Starting the analysis</h3><p>If you see the command and type /c4, the plugin is correctly installed. By selecting the command and pressing Enter, you will start the command.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/01-c4-command.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="1528" height="418" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/01-c4-command.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/01-c4-command.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/01-c4-command.png 1528w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Typing the C4 command in Claude Code (Visual Studio Code)</span></figcaption></figure><p>The command initiates the entire skill on Claude Code.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/2-c4-command.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="2000" height="1286" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/2-c4-command.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/2-c4-command.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1600/2026/02/2-c4-command.png 1600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w2400/2026/02/2-c4-command.png 2400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Starting the C4 skill in Claude Code</span></figcaption></figure><p>While analyzing the entire codebase, it will ask you for some C4 specifics, such as which views you would like to specify in the DSL.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/04-c4-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="2000" height="622" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/04-c4-1.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/04-c4-1.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1600/2026/02/04-c4-1.png 1600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w2400/2026/02/04-c4-1.png 2400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Selecting the architecture views based on the C4 model</span></figcaption></figure><p>Additionally, you will be asked which part of Supabase you want to analyze because it is a large codebase.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/05-c4.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="2000" height="497" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/05-c4.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/05-c4.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1600/2026/02/05-c4.png 1600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w2400/2026/02/05-c4.png 2400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Selecting the scope of the architecture analysis</span></figcaption></figure><p>After analyzing the codebase, the skill can write the architecture model using the Structurizr DSL in a workspace.dsl file.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/06-c4-skill-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="2000" height="1189" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/06-c4-skill-1.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/06-c4-skill-1.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1600/2026/02/06-c4-skill-1.png 1600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w2400/2026/02/06-c4-skill-1.png 2400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Writing the architecture model in Structurizr DSL based workspace.dsl</span></figcaption></figure><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/07-c4-skill.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="2000" height="1221" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/07-c4-skill.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/07-c4-skill.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1600/2026/02/07-c4-skill.png 1600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w2400/2026/02/07-c4-skill.png 2400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Analyzing the finished architecture model and all views created based on the written Structurizr DSL.</span></figcaption></figure><p>Here you will find the completed workspace.dsl file for Supabase, which can be viewed at <a href="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/a-simple-5-step-approach-to-support-any-new-initiative-as-a-software-architect/" rel="noreferrer">playground.structurizr.com</a>, along with all generated architecture diagrams.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"><a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://gist.github.com/bitsmuggler/8ba562adc88a413923e95c139451b877?ref=workingsoftware.dev"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">Generated Supabase Architecture Model in Structurizr DSL (workingsoftware.dev)</div><div class="kg-bookmark-description">Generated Supabase Architecture Model in Structurizr DSL (workingsoftware.dev) - workspace.dsl</div><div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/icon/pinned-octocat-093da3e6fa40-14.svg" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code"><span class="kg-bookmark-author">Gist</span><span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">262588213843476</span></div></div><div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/thumbnail/gist-og-image-54fd7dc0713e-1.png" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" onerror="this.style.display = &apos;none&apos;"></div></a></figure><h3 id="reviewing-the-created-views">Reviewing the created views</h3><p><strong>Level 1: System Context View</strong></p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/structurizr-SystemContext-2.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="1045" height="901" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/structurizr-SystemContext-2.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/structurizr-SystemContext-2.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/structurizr-SystemContext-2.png 1045w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Generated System Context Diagram with C4-PlantUML</span></figcaption></figure><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="2000" height="891" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/image.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/image.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1600/2026/02/image.png 1600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/image.png 2251w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Generated Context Diagram with PlantUML</span></figcaption></figure><p><strong>Level 2: Container View (all containers)</strong></p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-grey"><div class="kg-callout-emoji">&#x2757;</div><div class="kg-callout-text">The first version of the skill it generates all containers in one view. This should probably improved. It doesn&apos;t make sense to have such big overview diagrams. Ideally, there are several with with selected person and containers (e.g. per per person, per use case, per what ever which makes sense for the communication).</div></div><p></p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/structurizr-Containers.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="2000" height="1886" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/structurizr-Containers.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/structurizr-Containers.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1600/2026/02/structurizr-Containers.png 1600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/structurizr-Containers.png 2282w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Generated Container Diagram with C4-PlantUML</span></figcaption></figure><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2026/02/structurizr-Containers-1.png" class="kg-image" alt="AI-Assisted Software Architecture: Generating the C4 Model and Views Directly from Code" loading="lazy" width="2000" height="1069" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2026/02/structurizr-Containers-1.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2026/02/structurizr-Containers-1.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1600/2026/02/structurizr-Containers-1.png 1600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w2400/2026/02/structurizr-Containers-1.png 2400w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Generated Container Diagram with PlantUML</span></figcaption></figure><p>This is a first draft of a C4 architecture skill for Claude Code. It provides an initial overview of the major building blocks and third-party dependencies of your system. This was my first attempt to support AI-assisted software architecture work.</p><p>I hope this helps as a software architect! But be aware - the code doesn&apos;t tell the whole story &#x1F609;.</p><p>Let me know if you have any feedback or thoughts on this idea.</p><p>Thank you.</p>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect]]></title><description><![CDATA[A simple 5-step approach for Software Architects to guide new initiatives: align on the problem, map the landscape, define boundaries, and set direction.]]></description><link>https://www.workingsoftware.dev/a-simple-5-step-approach-to-support-any-new-initiative-as-a-software-architect/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">692c18b4b9fb3e00013d5269</guid><category><![CDATA[Software Architecture]]></category><category><![CDATA[Software Architect]]></category><category><![CDATA[Jobs-to-be-done Canvas]]></category><category><![CDATA[Event Storming]]></category><category><![CDATA[Wardley Mapping]]></category><category><![CDATA[Architecture Decision Canvas]]></category><category><![CDATA[Context Mapping]]></category><dc:creator><![CDATA[Patrick Roos]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 30 Nov 2025 10:36:49 GMT</pubDate><media:content url="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/a-simple-5-step-approach.png" medium="image"/><content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/a-simple-5-step-approach.png" alt="A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect"><p>Supporting a new initiative as a Software Architect involves more than just selecting technology &#x2013; it requires establishing clarity, boundaries, and direction in an environment full of uncertainty. </p><p>Over the years, I&#x2019;ve learned that architecture is most effective when it begins before any discussion of systems, patterns, or technologies.</p><p>That&#x2019;s why I use a straightforward five-step architectural approach for every new initiative:</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/2-3.png" class="kg-image" alt="A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect" loading="lazy" width="1200" height="1200" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2025/11/2-3.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2025/11/2-3.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/2-3.png 1200w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Overview of the simple 5-step approach to support an software initiative as a software architect</span></figcaption></figure><h2 id="understand-the-problem">Understand the Problem</h2><p>Before architecture can exist, the problem must exist.</p><p>Using a <a href="https://strategyn.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Strategyn_JTBD-Market-Definition_Canvas.pdf?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">Jobs-to-Be-Done Canvas</a> helps teams describe the initiative from a value and outcome perspective, not from solutions.</p><p>This prevents premature architecture decisions and anchors later system design in real user needs.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/3-3.png" class="kg-image" alt="A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect" loading="lazy" width="1200" height="1200" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2025/11/3-3.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2025/11/3-3.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/3-3.png 1200w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Align on the problem the initiative solves</span></figcaption></figure><h2 id="understand-the-landscape">Understand the landscape</h2><p>Architecture is strategy.</p><p>A <a href="https://learnwardleymapping.com/?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">Wardley Map</a> shows:</p><ul><li>where the initiative fits in the value chain</li><li>which components should be built, bought, or commoditized</li><li>and where innovation or industrialization is needed.</li></ul><p>This prevents overengineering and aligns architecture with business strategy.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/4-3.png" class="kg-image" alt="A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect" loading="lazy" width="1200" height="1200" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2025/11/4-3.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2025/11/4-3.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/4-3.png 1200w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Understanding the landscape with Wardley Mapping</span></figcaption></figure><h2 id="understand-the-domain">Understand the Domain</h2><p>Architecture emerges from domain understanding.</p><p>Through <a href="https://www.eventstorming.com/?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">Event Storming</a>, we build shared terminology, flows, and subdomains.</p><p>This step is crucial because:</p><ul><li>domain language defines bounded contexts</li><li>domain flows guide system decomposition</li><li>domain complexity determines architecture complexity.</li></ul><p>Every good architecture begins with shared understanding.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/5-3.png" class="kg-image" alt="A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect" loading="lazy" width="1200" height="1200" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2025/11/5-3.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2025/11/5-3.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/5-3.png 1200w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Understanding the Domain with Event Storming</span></figcaption></figure><h2 id="define-boundaries-and-team-ownership">Define boundaries and team ownership</h2><p>With <a href="https://github.com/ddd-crew/context-mapping?ref=workingsoftware.dev" rel="noreferrer">Context Mapping</a>, architectural boundaries become team boundaries. </p><p>This turns domain insight into bounded contexts, integration contracts, upstream and downstream relationships, and team responsibilities. </p><p>This is when architecture becomes organizationally real - not just theoretical.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/6-3.png" class="kg-image" alt="A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect" loading="lazy" width="1200" height="1200" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2025/11/6-3.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2025/11/6-3.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/6-3.png 1200w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Define boundaries and team ownership with context mapping</span></figcaption></figure><h2 id="make-initial-architecture-hypotheses">Make initial architecture hypotheses</h2><p>With the problem, landscape, and domain understood, we can define the technology direction.</p><p>The <a href="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/introducing-the-software-architecture-decision-canvas/" rel="noreferrer">Architecture Decision Canvas</a> helps collaboratively elaborate on the initial architectural hypotheses.</p><p>This ensures early alignment and gives teams a clear runway.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/7-3.png" class="kg-image" alt="A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect" loading="lazy" width="1200" height="1200" srcset="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w600/2025/11/7-3.png 600w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/size/w1000/2025/11/7-3.png 1000w, https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/7-3.png 1200w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Work on first architecture decisions with the </span><a href="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/introducing-the-software-architecture-decision-canvas/"><span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Architecture Decision Canvas</span></a></figcaption></figure><p>If you&apos;re looking for additional techniques to support software architects, check out the other post below.</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"><a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/fundamental-techniques-for-software-architects/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">30 Fundamental Techniques for Software Architects</div><div class="kg-bookmark-description">Discover essential techniques for software architects to design modern systems, align with business goals, and manage stakeholders effectively. Learn more in this post!</div><div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/icon/logo_small_icon_only-1-13.png" alt="A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect"><span class="kg-bookmark-author">workingsoftware.dev</span><span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Patrick Roos</span></div></div><div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/thumbnail/White-Simple-Business-Blog-Banner--1-.png" alt="A simple 5-step approach to support any new initiative as a Software Architect" onerror="this.style.display = &apos;none&apos;"></div></a></figure>]]></content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Wardley Mapping Doctrine: 40 Principles for Smarter Strategic Decisions]]></title><description><![CDATA[Explore a set of universal principles for strategic success, focusing on situational awareness, user needs, and adaptability in dynamic environments.]]></description><link>https://www.workingsoftware.dev/wardley-mapping-doctrine/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">691cd7a2dde30a0001c3f223</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Patrick Roos]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 18 Nov 2025 20:42:57 GMT</pubDate><media:content url="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-Copy-of-White-Simple-Business-Blog-Banner--1-.png" medium="image"/><content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="https://www.workingsoftware.dev/content/images/2025/11/Copy-of-C